Message(content='```json\n{\n  "[Question 1] - What is the problem?": "How can we improve the alignment of text-to-image generative models with human preferences while maintaining output diversity and reducing computational demands, without relying solely on reverse Kullback-Leibler divergence penalties?",\n  "[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?": "Solving this problem is crucial for advancing the reliability and usability of text-to-image models in real-world applications. It addresses the critical issue of diversity in generated outputs, which is essential for creativity and practical utility. By reducing computational demands, we can make these models more accessible and scalable. This research will influence future work in model alignment, potentially leading to more robust and versatile generative systems.",\n  "[Question 3] - Why is it hard?": "The challenge lies in balancing model alignment with human preferences and maintaining diversity in outputs. Naive approaches may lead to overfitting or instability. Technical obstacles include the complexity of training with diverse divergence constraints and the need for efficient computational methods. Theoretical challenges involve understanding the interplay between different divergence measures and their impact on model behavior.",\n  "[Question 4] - Why hasn\'t it been solved before?": "Previous research has predominantly focused on reverse KL divergence, which has limitations in terms of diversity and computational efficiency. There is a gap in exploring alternative divergence measures and their integration into the alignment process. Existing solutions often require significant computational resources and may not fully address the diversity issue.",\n  "[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?": "The proposed approach involves developing a framework that incorporates multiple divergence constraints (e.g., Jensen-Shannon divergence) into the RLHF pipeline. We will us