xity of RLHF pipelines, the tendency of models to overfit on a few images, and the difficulty in balancing alignment with diversity. Naive approaches may fail due to the intricate nature of human preferences and the high-dimensional space of possible images.\n\n**[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**\nPrevious research has primarily focused on reverse KL divergence, which tends to reduce diversity and introduce overfitting. There is a need to explore alternative divergence measures and implicit reward methods that can address these issues.\n\n**[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**\nThe proposed methodology involves developing a framework that combines multiple divergences, such as Jensen-Shannon divergence, to balance alignment and diversity. We will extend implicit reward methods like DPO to text-to-image models and evaluate their performance on benchmark datasets. The expected outcomes include improved alignment with human preferences, enhanced diversity in generated images, and more efficient RLHF pipelines."} {"type": "action_response", "result": "To refine the research idea to align with my expertise in computational chemistry and machine learning, particularly in molecular conformation generation and drug discovery, I will follow the outlined steps:\n\n### Reframing the Problem Setting\n- **Shift the focus from text-to-image models to generative models for molecular structures.**\n- **Highlight the importance of aligning these models with human preferences in the context of drug discovery and material design.**\n\n### Adjusting Prior Approaches\n- **Discuss how existing methods in molecular modeling, such as ConfGF and GeoDiff, can be adapted to incorporate human preferences.**\n- **Mention the challenges specific to molecular modeling, such as the complexity of 3D structures and the need for high accuracy.**\n\n### Identifying Implied Gaps\n- **Emphasize the need for methods that can generate diverse and accura