e diverse divergence measures (e.g., Jensen-Shannon divergence, Wasserstein distance) to improve output diversity. This framework will dynamically select the most appropriate divergence measure based on the specific task or dataset.\n- **Implementing Hybrid Approaches:** Combine explicit reward models with implicit reward methods, such as Direct Preference Optimization (DPO) and reinforcement learning with reverse KL divergence. This will leverage the strengths of both approaches to enhance alignment with human preferences.\n- **Optimizing RLHF Pipelines:** Develop more efficient algorithms for training reward models and fine-tuning text-to-image models. Explore techniques to reduce memory usage and computational demands in RLHF pipelines, possibly through model compression or efficient data handling.\n- **Diversity-Preserving Techniques:** Implement techniques to encourage diversity in generated outputs, such as using noise injection or enforcing diversity constraints during training. Develop methods to evaluate and measure output diversity in text-to-image models.\n- **Evaluating the Proposed Methods:** Evaluate the effectiveness of the proposed methods using a diverse set of text-to-image models and datasets, including both synthetic and real-world data. Expected outcomes include improved alignment with human preferences, increased output diversity, and more efficient RLHF pipelines.\n\n### Summary of the Refined Research Proposal\n\n**Problem Statement:** The problem is to improve the alignment of text-to-image generative models with human preferences while maintaining output diversity and reducing computational demands.\n\n**Importance:** This research is important for advancing practical applications of text-to-image models, ensuring they are reliable, user-friendly, and aligned with human values.\n\n**Challenges:** The challenges include defining human preferences, managing computational demands, and addressing the limitations of reverse KL divergence.\n\n**Approach:**\n1. **Diverse Divergences Framework:** Incorporate and dynamically select diverse divergence measures.\n2. **Hybrid Approaches:** Combine explicit and implicit reward methods.\n3. **Optimized RLHF Pipelines:** Develop efficient algorithms and techniques to reduce memory and computational demands.\n4. **Diversity-Preserving Techniques:** Implement methods to encourage and measure output diversity.\n\n**Expected Outcomes:** Improved alignment with human preferences, increased output diversity, and more efficient RLHF pipelines.\n\nThis refined research proposal is clear, specific, and aligned with my research goals and expertise in machine learning, probabilistic modeling, and decision-making.\n"}], 'summary': '```json\n{\n  "[Question 1] - What is the problem?": "How can we enhance the alignment of text-to-image generative models with human preferences while maintaining output diversity and reducing computational demands?",\n\n  "[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?": "Solving this problem is crucial for advancing the practical applications of text-to-image models, ensuring they generate images that are not only semantically coherent but also diverse and aligned with human values. This research will contribute to the development of more reliable and user-friendly AI systems, particularly in safety-critical applications where model calibration and uncertainty quantification are essential. Addressing these challenges will lead to more robust models that can be trusted in real-world scenarios, enhancing both the research community\'s understanding and the broader societal impact of generative AI technologies.",\n\n  "[Question 3] - Why is it hard?": "The challenges in solving this problem include the complexity of defining human preferences accurately, the computational demands of reinforcement learning pipelines, and the risk of overfitting and reduced diversity in generated outputs. Naive approaches may fail due to the difficulty in balancing